initial_story:
The National Police Air Service has shared a video of what it was like flying through Storm Gerrit's heavy winds, in a helicopter.

The footage, which was captured from inside the cockpit, shows the chopper rocking side to side, after being hit by winds of up to 80mph (128km/h).

Posting on X, formerly known as Twitter, the NPAS said "If you think it's windy down there, spare a thought for us up here in our flying washing machine".

The footage was filmed near Lea Valley reservoirs, North London.
stories: The pilots can be seen holding on to the controls tightly, their faces set with concentration, as they battle to keep the helicopter steady.
The rotors whirred loudly as the machine lurched violently, sending the pilots' heads snapping back and forth, their eyes darting wildly between the instrument panels and the turbulent sky outside.

The altimeter needle quivered wildly, struggling to keep pace with the erratic descent, while the airspeed indicator spun wildly out of control, its needle shuddering against the red line marked "Maximum G-Force".

The pilot's grip on the yoke tightened, her knuckles white with tension, as she fought to level off the aircraft's plunge, the engines roaring in protest as they strained to produce the necessary lift.
The altimeter needle was spinning wildly, and the horizon had disappeared from view, replaced by a swirling vortex of grey and green that seemed to be closing in on them from all sides.

The pilot's voice was steady, but a hint of panic crept into his tone as he called out, "Mayday, Mayday, this is Delta-7-Bravo, we're experiencing extreme turbulence and losing altitude rapidly, request emergency assistance at your earliest possible..."

"...coordinated location, our altitude is currently at 15,000 feet and dropping, we have multiple injuries on board and our navigation system is malfunctioning, repeat, mayday, mayday, Delta-7-Bravo in distress, please respond with emergency instructions."

"Roger that, Delta-7-Bravo, this is Air Traffic Control, we read your mayday call loud and clear. We're scrambling emergency responders and vectoring a nearby aircraft to your location. Can you give us a bearing and your estimated time of impact? Over."

"This is Delta-7-Bravo, roger that. My bearing is 245 degrees magnetic, and I'm estimating impact in approximately 10 minutes. I've got multiple system failures and I'm losing altitude fast, but I'm trying to maintain control. Over."

"Roger that, Delta-7-Bravo. Your situation is critical. Can you give me a status update on your engines? Are you still getting power from all three? And what's your current altitude and velocity? Over."

"This is Delta-7-Bravo. Engine one is offline, engine two is sputtering, and engine three is still giving me partial power. My current altitude is 20,000 feet and my velocity is approximately 350 knots. I'm experiencing severe turbulence and my wings are taking a beating. Requesting emergency descent and possible assistance with emergency landing. Over."

"This is Delta-7-Bravo. Receiving your message. Can you confirm your location and estimated time of emergency landing? We have a search and rescue team on standby, but we need to pinpoint your exact position to dispatch the necessary assets. Also, can you give me a status update on your life raft and emergency beacons? Over."

"This is Delta-7-Bravo. Roger that. My location is approximately 30 miles off the coast of Madagascar, bearing 270 degrees. Estimated time of emergency landing is 30 minutes, pending weather conditions. Life raft is deployed and inflated, but taking on water at a moderate rate. Emergency beacons are functioning, but signal strength is weak due to heavy cloud cover. Requesting priority dispatch of search and rescue assets to assist with recovery. Over."

"Roger that, Delta-7-Bravo. Affirmative on life raft status. Estimated time of emergency landing stands at 30 minutes, pending weather conditions. Requesting confirmation of any nearby assets, including naval or air units, that may be able to provide assistance. Additionally, requesting weather update and expected duration of heavy cloud cover. Over."

"Roger that, Delta-7-Bravo. This is Echo-1-Foxtrot. Confirming receipt of your message. As of last report, naval assets are approximately 20 miles due east, but air traffic is grounded due to weather conditions. Weather update: heavy cloud cover expected to persist for at least the next 2 hours, with scattered thunderstorms in the area. Requesting further clarification on emergency landing site coordinates and expected vector. Over."

"Roger that, Echo-1-Foxtrot. This is Delta-7-Bravo. Coordinates for emergency landing site are 43.7219° N, 72.3573° W. Vector is 270 degrees, heading 12 miles northwest of current position. Expecting moderate winds at 10 knots and turbulence at 5,000 feet. Requesting confirmation of reception and any further updates on naval assets and air traffic. Over."

"Roger that, Delta-7-Bravo. Echo-1-Foxtrot confirms reception of coordinates and vector. We are currently at 4,500 feet, adjusting course to 270 degrees. Turbulence at 5,000 feet will be a challenge, but we're prepared to navigate. No updates on naval assets or air traffic at this time. Requesting further updates as soon as available. Over."

"Roger that, Echo-1-Foxtrot. Delta-7-Bravo confirms reception of update. Continuing to adjust course to 270 degrees. Requesting a heads-up on any changes to weather patterns and turbulence in the area. Also, can you patch through to Sierra-1-Charlie for a status update on their position? Over."

"Roger that, Delta-7-Bravo. Weather patterns in the area are currently showing moderate turbulence with scattered cumulus clouds at 10,000 feet. I'll patch through to Sierra-1-Charlie for a status update. Hold for one. (pause) Sierra-1-Charlie, this is Echo-1-Foxtrot. Can you give me your updated position and estimated time of arrival at the rendezvous point? Over."

"Sierra-1-Charlie, this is Sierra-1-Charlie. We're currently 20 miles east of the rendezvous point, making good time at 300 knots. Estimated time of arrival is 15 minutes, assuming no further changes in weather patterns. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. This is Sierra-2-Bravo. We're 5 miles behind you, at 280 knots, and expecting to arrive at the rendezvous point around the same time. We've got a visual on your plane, and all systems are functioning within normal parameters. Can you confirm the weather situation at the rendezvous point? Are there any changes to the mission briefing?"

"Roger that, Sierra-2-Bravo. This is Sierra-1-Charlie. Visual contact is also maintained. Weather at the rendezvous point is clear, with a low ceiling at 1,500 feet and moderate turbulence. Mission briefing remains unchanged, with the exception of a minor alteration to the drop zone coordinates. I'm updating my navigation system as we speak. Confirming all systems are green here, including comms and avionics. We're expecting a smooth insertion. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. Sierra-2-Bravo, this is Sierra-1-Charlie. I concur with the updated drop zone coordinates. My navigation system is also updated, and I'm showing a direct route to the new coordinates. Confirming all systems are also green here, including comms and avionics. I'm expecting a smooth insertion as well. We're five minutes from the rendezvous point. Requesting a final status check from Sierra-2-Bravo before we go in. Over."

"Sierra-1-Charlie, this is Sierra-2-Bravo. Roger that, I concur with the updated drop zone coordinates and have also updated my navigation system. All systems are also green here, including comms and avionics. I'm showing a direct route to the new coordinates and expect a smooth insertion as well. We're also five minutes from the rendezvous point. I've completed my final checks and am ready to proceed. Confirming all packages are secure and ready for drop. Over."

"Sierra-2-Bravo, this is Sierra-1-Charlie. Roger that, all good here as well. I've also completed my final checks and am ready to proceed. Confirming all packages are secure and ready for drop. I'm also showing a direct route to the new coordinates and expect a smooth insertion. We're now four minutes from the rendezvous point. Let's proceed with caution and maintain secure comms. Over."

"Sierra-1-Charlie, roger that. I'm showing all clear as well. Beginning descent now. Please confirm you're on track to meet me at the designated coordinates. I'm also running a final scan for any potential threats. All systems go, over."

"Affirmative, Sierra-1-Charlie. I'm descending and tracking on course for the designated coordinates. Running a final systems check myself. Everything looks good from my end. Scanning for any last-minute threats. Reading you loud and clear, over."
"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. This is Mother-Base. Scanning your transponder. Please confirm your identity and mission designation, over."

"Roger that, Mother-Base. This is Sierra-1-Charlie. My identity is Captain Maximillian Sterling, and my mission designation is Operation Starlight. Scanning complete. Report: we have encountered an unknown alien presence in sector 7-9. Requesting guidance and backup, over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. This is Mother-Base. Captain Sterling, we're receiving your transmission loud and clear. Operation Starlight is a go, but we need to confirm the alien presence. Can you provide more details on the encounter? What's the nature of the alien lifeform? Are you experiencing any hostile intentions? And can you give us your current location and status, over?"

"Roger that, Mother-Base. Sierra-1-Charlie here. We're currently 300 kilometers north of the initial landing site, and we've confirmed the presence of the alien lifeform. It's a large, towering creature with multiple limbs and a bulbous head. We've attempted to communicate, but so far, it's shown no signs of understanding our language. We're not experiencing any hostile intentions, but we're cautious due to its size and unknown capabilities. We're currently assessing its movements and searching for any signs of technology or infrastructure. Our status is green, with full power and life support systems online. We'll continue to monitor the creature's movements and provide updates as necessary. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. Mother-Base acknowledges your situation report. We're sending additional parameters to your comms device to enhance your language analysis software. We're also initiating a database search for any similar encounters or species profiles. In the meantime, proceed with caution and maintain a safe distance. If you encounter any signs of technology or infrastructure, do not attempt to interact or damage it. We're also sending a drone to provide additional reconnaissance and support. ETA is 20 minutes. Keep us updated on the creature's movements and any changes to your status. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. Drone's ETA acknowledged. I'm moving to a safe distance to await its arrival. The creature is currently stationary, but I'm keeping a close eye on it. No signs of technology or infrastructure in sight. I'll continue to monitor its movements and report any changes. Also, can you confirm if the language analysis software update includes any protocols for potential communication with the creature? Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. Update on the software package is being sent to your encrypted comms device as we speak. It includes a custom-built protocol for attempting to establish a communication link with the creature, as well as advanced language pattern recognition algorithms. We're also sending a secondary protocol to analyze any potential biometric or behavioral patterns exhibited by the creature. Be advised to prioritize caution and avoid any direct contact until further instructions. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. Acknowledged receipt of update. Beginning download and encryption protocols now. Will prioritize caution and avoid direct contact until further instructions. Requesting additional intel on creature's last known location and any observed behavior patterns. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. Last known location is coordinates 43.7821° N, 79.4165° W, approximately 20 kilometers north of the abandoned research facility. Observed behavior patterns indicate erratic movement, possible aggressive displays towards any perceived threats. Caution advised. Additionally, requesting any available satellite imagery or reconnaissance reports on the surrounding area. Be advised, all communication channels are being monitored. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. Satellite imagery received, showing unusual energy signatures emanating from the research facility. Recommendation: deploy reconnaissance team to investigate further and gather intel on the situation. Advise against engaging with the erratic entity unless absolutely necessary. Requesting confirmation of the entity's current status and any new coordinates. Over."

"Roger that, HQ. Sierra-1-Charlie confirms receipt of intel. Reconnaissance team deployed, ETA 30 minutes to the research facility. Entity status currently unknown, but reports indicate increased seismic activity and electromagnetic disruptions in the area. Requesting additional satellite imagery and any available data on the facility's research projects. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. HQ is sending over updated satellite imagery and research project files. Be advised, we're also sending a backup team to the research facility, ETA 1 hour. Requesting Sierra-1-Charlie to maintain contact with the reconnaissance team and provide situation reports. Over."

"Roger that, HQ. Sierra-1-Charlie acknowledges receipt of updated satellite imagery and research project files. We're on the move to intercept the reconnaissance team and establish comms. ETA to the research facility is approximately 45 minutes. Requesting additional intel on the nature of the situation at the facility and any known hostile forces. Over."

"Roger that, Sierra-1-Charlie. HQ acknowledges receipt of your sitrep. Intel suggests the research facility is currently occupied by a team of scientists and support staff, but we have reason to believe they may be in contact with an unknown third party. We're working to verify the nature of the situation, but so far, all attempts at communication have been met with silence. Requesting you to exercise extreme caution and be prepared for any eventuality. ETA to the facility is still approximately 45 minutes. Over."

"Roger that, HQ. Sierra-1-Charlie copies all. I'll proceed with extreme caution and prepare for any scenario. Requesting confirmation on the composition of the team and any known security protocols in place. Also, can you provide an update on the status of the unknown third party? Is there any indication of their intentions or capabilities? Over."

"HQ this is Sierra-1-Charlie. Roger your confirmation of caution. Composition of team is still unknown, but our sources indicate a mix of military and civilian personnel. Security protocols are likely to be standard issue, but we've received reports of advanced biometric scanners and possible AI integration. As for the unknown third party, intel suggests they may be a rogue state actor, but we're still waiting on concrete evidence. We're also seeing some unusual energy signatures in the area, which may be related to their presence. Over."

"Sierra-1-Charlie, this is HQ. Roger confirmation of caution. Intel on the unknown third party is still developing, but we're working on verifying the energy signatures. Can you confirm the location of the biometric scanners and AI integration? Are they centralized or scattered throughout the area? Also, have you received any further information on the composition of the team, including any high-value targets or sensitive equipment? Over."

"Sierra-1-Charlie, this is HQ. Roger that. We've got eyes on the biometric scanners, and they're scattered throughout the area, with a central hub controlling access to the facility. AI integration is moderate, with some autonomous systems in place, but we're seeing no indication of a fully autonomous operation. As for the team, we're still trying to gather more intel, but so far we've identified two high-value targets: Dr. Rachel Kim, lead researcher on the project, and Dr. Liam Chen, a robotics engineer. We're still working on pinpointing their exact location. Over."

"Sierra-1-Charlie, this is HQ. Roger that. We've got an update on the high-value targets. Dr. Rachel Kim was last seen heading to the central hub, likely to access the facility's mainframe. Dr. Liam Chen was spotted near the east wing, where the robotics lab is located. We're going to try to get a lock on their comms devices to get a better fix on their location. Can you move to intercept Dr. Kim at the central hub and try to grab her before she accesses the mainframe? We don't want her to warn the other targets. Over."

"Sierra-1-Charlie, roger that. I'm en route to the central hub now. I'll try to move stealthy and avoid drawing attention to myself. Can you give me an ETA on when we can expect to get a lock on Dr. Kim's comms device? And what's the status on Dr. Chen's location? Is he still at the robotics lab or has he moved? Over."

"Sierra-1-Charlie, this is Base. Roger your ETA, you should be able to reach the central hub in about 20 minutes. As for the comms device, our techs are working on it now, but it's not looking good. Dr. Kim's team has implemented some heavy encryption, and it's going to take some time to crack it. As for Dr. Chen, our last update had him still at the robotics lab, but we're getting some strange readings that suggest he might be moving. We're trying to pinpoint his location, but it's like he's ghosting us. Be careful, Sierra-1-Charlie. You're not the only one looking for Dr. Chen. Over."

"Roger that, Base. ETA is 20 minutes, and I'll keep an eye out for any signs of Dr. Chen. I'm getting a little spooked about these strange readings, though. Can you try to get me a visual on the lab? I want to know if Dr. Chen is moving or if this is just some kind of malfunction. And what's the situation with the comms device? Is there any chance of getting a message to Dr. Kim or Dr. Chen directly? Over."

"Roger that, Ranger. Visual on the lab is negative, but I've got a satellite image of the area coming up now. As for the comms device, I've tried hacking into it, but it's encrypted and I'm not having any luck cracking the code. I'll keep working on it, but in the meantime, I'm going to try to raise Dr. Kim on a separate frequency. Hold tight, and keep your eyes peeled for any signs of Dr. Chen. ETA 15 minutes. Over."
